        contentMd: "# Hypothalamus & Pituitary - Mechanisms\n\n## Growth Hormone (GH)\n### Secretion Pattern\n- Pulsatile, **maximum during deep sleep** (NREM stage 3-4)\n- Peak during puberty, declines with age\n- Stimulated by: GHRH, ghrelin, sleep, exercise, hypoglycemia, arginine\n- Inhibited by: Somatostatin, IGF-1, hyperglycemia, obesity\n\n### Mechanism of Action\n- Acts via **JAK2-STAT5 pathway** (tyrosine kinase receptor)\n- **Direct**: Lipolysis, insulin resistance, protein synthesis\n- **Indirect** (via IGF-1 from liver): Linear growth, chondrogenesis\n\n## Prolactin\n- Tonic inhibition by dopamine (tuberoinfundibular pathway)\n- Stimulated by: TRH, suckling, estrogen, sleep, stress\n- Acts via JAK2-STAT5\n- Functions: Milk synthesis, inhibits GnRH (lactational amenorrhea)\n\n## ADH (Vasopressin)\n### Stimuli for Release\n- **Osmotic** (primary): Osmoreceptors in OVLT detect >280 mOsm/kg\n- **Non-osmotic**: Hypovolemia, pain, nausea\n\n### Receptors\n| Receptor | Location | Effect |\n|----------|----------|--------|\n| V1 (Gq) | Vascular smooth muscle | Vasoconstriction |\n| V2 (Gs) | Collecting duct | Aquaporin-2 insertion, water reabsorption |\n| V3 (Gq) | Anterior pituitary | ACTH release |\n\n## Oxytocin\n- **Milk ejection reflex**: Suckling → oxytocin → myoepithelial contraction\n- **Ferguson reflex**: Cervical distension → oxytocin → uterine contraction (positive feedback)",
