        contentMd: "# Clinical Applications\n\n## GH Disorders\n| Condition | Features |\n|-----------|----------|\n| **Gigantism** | GH excess before epiphyseal closure — tall stature |\n| **Acromegaly** | GH excess after closure — enlarged hands/feet/jaw |\n| **Laron dwarfism** | GH receptor defect — high GH, low IGF-1 |\n\n- Acromegaly diagnosis: OGTT (GH not suppressed below 1 ng/mL)\n- Treatment: Trans-sphenoidal surgery, octreotide, pegvisomant\n\n## Diabetes Insipidus\n| Type | ADH Level | Desmopressin Response |\n|------|-----------|----------------------|\n| Central DI | Low | Responds |\n| Nephrogenic DI | High | No response |\n\n- Polyuria >3L/day, dilute urine, water deprivation test\n\n## SIADH\n- Excess ADH → dilutional hyponatremia\n- Causes: Small cell lung CA, CNS disorders, carbamazepine\n- Treatment: Fluid restriction, tolvaptan (V2 antagonist)\n\n## Sheehan Syndrome\n- Postpartum pituitary necrosis from hemorrhage\n- Earliest sign: **failure of lactation** (lactotrophs most sensitive)\n- Common in India due to postpartum hemorrhage\n\n> **Clinical Pearl**: In Sheehan syndrome, failure to lactate is the earliest sign because lactotrophs are the most sensitive to ischemia.",
