        summary: "T3/T4 synthesis steps, nuclear receptor mechanism, deiodinase enzymes, Wolff-Chaikoff and Jod-Basedow effects.",
        contentMd: "# Thyroid Hormone Synthesis & Action\n\n## Steps of Synthesis\n1. **Trapping**: NIS on basolateral membrane (TSH-stimulated)\n2. **Oxidation**: I- → I0 by **TPO** using H2O2\n3. **Organification**: Iodine + tyrosine on thyroglobulin → MIT, DIT\n4. **Coupling**: MIT+DIT → **T3**; DIT+DIT → **T4** (by TPO)\n5. **Storage**: As colloid (2-3 months supply)\n6. **Release**: Endocytosis → lysosomal proteolysis → T3/T4 released\n7. **Recycling**: MIT/DIT deiodinated by dehalogenase\n\n- **TPO** is the key enzyme — target of anti-TPO antibodies (Hashimoto)\n- PTU and methimazole inhibit TPO\n\n## Deiodinase Enzymes\n| Type | Location | Function |\n|------|----------|----------|\n| D1 | Liver, kidney | T4 → T3 (peripheral) |\n| D2 | Brain, pituitary | T4 → T3 (local) |\n| D3 | Placenta, brain | T4 → rT3 (inactivation) |\n\n## Mechanism of Action\n- T3 binds nuclear thyroid receptor (TR) → TRE on DNA\n- Increases Na+/K+ ATPase → calorigenic effect\n- Upregulates beta-adrenergic receptors\n\n## Wolff-Chaikoff Effect\n- Excess iodide inhibits organification temporarily\n- Escape in 2-4 weeks; used pre-surgery (Lugol iodine)\n\n## Jod-Basedow Effect\n- Excess iodide causes hyperthyroidism in autonomous tissue",
