        summary: "Cortisol actions and regulation, aldosterone mechanism, catecholamine synthesis and effects.",
        contentMd: "# Adrenal Gland - Mechanisms\n\n## Cortisol\n### Regulation\n- HPA axis: CRH → ACTH → Cortisol (negative feedback)\n- **Diurnal rhythm**: Peak at 6-8 AM, nadir at midnight\n- Stress overrides negative feedback\n\n### Actions\n- **Metabolic**: Gluconeogenesis (liver), protein catabolism (muscle), lipolysis (redistribution)\n- **Anti-inflammatory**: Inhibits PLA2 (via lipocortin), reduces IL-1/IL-6/TNF\n- **Immunosuppressive**: Lymphocyte apoptosis, neutrophilia\n- **CVS**: Permissive effect on catecholamines (maintains vascular tone)\n- **Bone**: Inhibits osteoblasts → osteoporosis\n- **CNS**: Euphoria initially, then depression\n\n### Mechanism of Action\n- Binds intracellular glucocorticoid receptor → translocates to nucleus → gene transcription\n- Carried in blood by **CBG (Cortisol-Binding Globulin/Transcortin)**\n\n## Aldosterone\n### Regulation\n- **RAAS** (primary), hyperkalemia, ACTH (minor)\n- NOT regulated by HPA axis primarily\n\n### Mechanism\n- Binds mineralocorticoid receptor in distal tubule/collecting duct\n- Increases ENaC (Na+ reabsorption) and ROMK (K+ secretion)\n- Net effect: Na+ retention, K+ and H+ excretion\n\n## Catecholamines\n### Synthesis\nTyrosine → DOPA (by TH, rate-limiting) → Dopamine → NE → Epi (by PNMT)\n\n### Receptors\n| Receptor | Effect |\n|----------|--------|\n| Alpha-1 | Vasoconstriction, mydriasis |\n| Alpha-2 | Presynaptic inhibition, decreased insulin |\n| Beta-1 | Heart: increased rate, contractility |\n| Beta-2 | Bronchodilation, vasodilation, glycogenolysis |\n| Beta-3 | Lipolysis |",
